# Only the top 10,000 most common terms in the training set will be retained, according to the input num_words=10000. We'll eliminate uncommon words. As a result, we are able to work with reasonably sized vector data.

# The lists of reviews that make up the variables train_data and test_data are lists of word indices, or word sequences encoded in each review. Lists containing 0s and 1s, where 0 represents "negative" and 1 represents "positive," make up train_labels and test_labels.

# As a result of our restriction to the top 10,000 most frequently occurring words, no word index will be higher than 10,000.
In [259]:
# Preparation of the Data

# Lists of integers cannot be fed into a neural network. Our lists must be transformed into tensors. We could accomplish that in two ways:

# 1. One possible solution is to create an integer tensor of the form samples, word_indices by padding our lists to make them of the same length. Then, we could use an Embedding layerwhich we will discuss in more detail later in the bookas the first layer in our network, which can handle these kinds of integer tensors.
# 2. To convert our lists into vectors of 0s and 1s, we could one-hot-encode them. To put it practically, this would entail, for example, converting the sequence [3, 5] into a 10,000-dimensional vector in which all of the indices are ones, with the exception of 3 and 5. An initial layer in our network may then be a dense layer that can handle floating point vector data.
# We'll choose the second option. Now let's vectorize our data, which will be done by hand for optimal clarity:
In [269]:
import numpy as np

def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension=10000):
    # Create an all-zero matrix of shape (len(sequences), dimension)
    results = np.zeros((len(sequences), dimension))
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        results[i, sequence] = 1.  # set specific indices of results[i] to 1s
    return results

# Our vectorized training data
x_train = vectorize_sequences(train_data)
# Our vectorized test data
x_test = vectorize_sequences(test_data)

# Conclusion
# Differently configured neural network models displayed varying patterns of loss and sensitivity. The Model_Hyper displayed the highest delicacy and the least loss of all of them because to its three tightly packed layers. The implication of this finding is that this particular configuration works well for interpreting the IMDB dataset. Moreover, the least amount of loss was obtained by employing the mean squared error (MSE) loss function, but the tanh activation function yielded less delicacy because to issues with vanishing gradients. The Adam optimizer was useful, while regularization techniques showed promise in reducing overfitting.We used dropout regularization in the trial's last phase to allay any worries about overfitting.
# By including dropout layers into a new model and running training and evaluation on both the training and test datasets, we observed a notable improvement in confirmation delicacy when compared to the baseline model. More specifically, dropout regularization enhanced model performance, lowering overfitting problems and boosting accuracy.
# The use of dropout regularization significantly improved the models' overall performance; of all the models evaluated, Model Hyper had the best performance. The comprehensive analysis that considered variations in sensitivity, loss, and the effects of different configurations shows that dropout regularization is an effective technique to increase the neural networks interpretive power.
